# Delegate grunt work to t2 code

Grind lane = **`t2code exec`** (the `@t2000/code` coding agent on Private
Inference / `t2000/auto`). This is dogfood for our own product — bulk steps
route cheap, hard steps auto-escalate. Burning frontier Cursor tokens on
mechanical work is the failure mode this rule exists to stop.

**Not `zero`.** `zero` was the interim Step-0 executor; do not use it.

## When to delegate (Grind)

A task qualifies when it is WELL-SPECIFIED and MECHANICAL — you could write
acceptance criteria in two sentences:

- sweeps (rename X→Y across files, update imports, fix lint warnings)
- make-the-tests-pass loops on a known suite
- boilerplate generation from an existing pattern
- doc/comment staleness sweeps with clear criteria

Do NOT Grind: ambiguous or architectural work, security-sensitive changes,
anything touching money paths (`packages/sdk` send/swap/pay logic), or tasks
where the spec IS the hard part. Those go to **Think** (Cursor) or **Build**
(Claude Code on Anthropic Max) — see `spend-lanes.mdc`.

## How

Same working tree (integrated terminal):

```bash
t2code exec "<task with explicit acceptance criteria>"
# noisy suites — keep output short so the agent transcript stays readable
t2code exec "run CI=true pnpm --filter <pkg> test 2>&1 | tail -40 and fix until green: <criteria>"
```

Prereq: `t2code login` with a console key (`T2000_API_KEY` / console mint) so
inference bills the Private Inference account — never put keys in the prompt.

- Monitor the run; when it finishes, REVIEW THE DIFF yourself (`git diff`)
  before reporting back. You own the result, not t2code.
- Never let t2code commit. Commits happen through the normal review flow.
- If t2code's result is wrong twice, stop Grind for that task class and escalate
  to Build (Claude Code) — note the misroute (eval fodder for
  `audric/apps/web-v3/scripts/api-router-eval.ts`).
